          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827203?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">埃隆·马斯克今年早些时候在北京。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：TINGSHU WANG/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100267"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alexa-corse" itemprop="url" rel="author">亚历克莎</a></span>·科西嘉</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 1 日凌晨 2:09 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musks-x-sues-nonprofit-that-accused-it-of-allowing-hate-speech-ee030062"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">埃隆·马斯克(Elon Musk)</a>的社交媒体公司正在起诉一家非营利组织，该非营利组织指责该平台允许仇恨言论扩散，从而加剧了这位亿万富翁与该研究小组之间持续的冲突。</p><p> X Corp.（前身为 Twitter）在周一向联邦法院提起的诉讼中声称，该组织（反数字仇恨中心）使用有缺陷的方法来准备其研究，以审查其不同意的观点。</p><p>该中心没有立即回应对该诉讼发表评论的请求。该组织此前曾为其研究进行辩护，并指责马斯克试图压制该研究。<br><br>对抗数字仇恨中心发表了几篇批评马斯克社交媒体公司的研究报告。 6 月份发表的一项研究称，研究人员称，在 100 条帖子中，99% 的帖子包含仇恨内容，Twitter 没有采取任何行动。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=6CE78F28-2BEA-4FE6-9CC6-467331986FF6&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Felon-musks-x-sues-nonprofit-that-accused-it-of-allowing-hate-speech-ee030062&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">工人们从这家公司（前身为 Twitter）旧金山总部的顶部拆除了一个巨大的闪烁 X 标志。该市表示收到了有关该装置的灯光和稳定性的投诉。照片：贾斯汀·沙利文/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>马斯克的公司对该组织的研究提出了质疑。 X Corp. 的律师亚历克斯·斯皮罗 (Alex Spiro) 于 7 月 20 日致函该中心，指责该中心提出“一系列令人不安且毫无根据的指控，这些指控似乎旨在损害 Twitter 的整体利益，特别是损害其数字广告业务”。斯皮罗在信中表示，该公司正在考虑采取法律行动。</p><p>在诉讼中，马斯克的公司指控反数字仇恨中心通过抓取和不当获取供应商运营的数据库的登录凭据，不当访问 X 平台的数据。该诉讼寻求陪审团审判、金钱赔偿以及禁止该集团及其员工访问与 X 平台相关的某些数据。</p><p>打击数字仇恨中心称这封信是企图恐吓他们。</p><p>该组织首席执行官伊姆兰·艾哈迈德 (Imran Ahmed) 在一份声明中表示：“马斯克之所以瞄准 CCDH，是因为我们揭露了他所拥有的 Twitter 上仇恨和虚假信息传播的真相，这影响了他的底线。”</p><p>这家社交媒体公司一直面临挑战，包括沉重的债务负担和去年年底马斯克斥资 440 亿美元收购后广告业务的下降。马斯克接手后，许多广告商退出了该平台，部分原因是担心他的内容审核方式。</p><p>马斯克<a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1680082007873953794?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1680082007873953794%7Ctwgr%5E4b0d552330bca5ec541f846f2df2a4fde28c3835%7Ctwcon%5Es1_&amp;ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Flivecoverage.dowjones.io%2Fwsj" target="_blank" class="icon none">在 7 月份的推文中表示，</a>广告收入下降了约 50%，公司现金流为负。</p><p>写信给 Alexa Corse： <a href="mailto:alexa.corse@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">alexa.corse@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 06:09:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musks-x-sues-nonprofit-that-accused-it-of-allowing-hate-speech-ee030062</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musks-x-sues-nonprofit-that-accused-it-of-allowing-hate-speech-ee030062<author><![CDATA[Alexa Corse]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台/工具</category><category>技术</category><category>企业犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>歧视</category><category>仇恨犯罪</category><category>高净值个人</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>社会问题</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>埃隆·马斯克</category><category>企业犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>歧视</category><category>仇恨犯罪</category><category>高净值个人</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>社会问题</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台</category><category>工具</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[X Sign Removed From Former Twitter HQ]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>星期五竖立在旧金山大楼顶上的 X 标志在居民投诉和市政府罚单后被拆除<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001099980"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="542" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827151?width=860&amp;height=542" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">根据该市建筑检查部网站上发现的投诉，屋顶上的工程未经许可进行。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：贾斯汀·沙利文/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001099980"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/lindsey-choo" itemprop="url" rel="author">林赛</a></span>·朱</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 31 日晚上 9:06 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/x-sign-removed-from-top-of-former-twitter-hq-59f5a9f0"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>在居民投诉以及市政府因缺乏许可证而发出违规通知后，工人们拆除了这家公司（前身为 Twitter）旧金山总部顶部的巨型 X 标志。</p><p> X（该公司现在的名称）于周五张贴了该标牌，但在接下来的几天里，该标牌的亮度和稳定性引起了居民的投诉。该市表示，该标牌张贴后，收到了 24 起与该标牌相关的投诉，理由是灯光和稳定性。该市表示，缺乏许可证可能会对公共安全和历史保护构成风险。</p><p> “关掉它！！目前它正在快速闪烁，并且极其明亮。它造成了巨大的夜间滋扰，让人难以入睡，”一位人士在向市政府的投诉中写道。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=6CE78F28-2BEA-4FE6-9CC6-467331986FF6&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fx-sign-removed-from-top-of-former-twitter-hq-59f5a9f0&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">工人们从这家公司（前身为 Twitter）旧金山总部的顶部拆除了一个巨大的闪烁 X 标志。该市表示收到了有关该装置的灯光和稳定性的投诉。照片：贾斯汀·沙利文/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>根据该市建筑检查部网站上发现的一份投诉，屋顶上的工程<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/x-formerly-known-as-twitter-reinstates-kanye-wests-account-7c8c70d2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">是在没有许可证的情况下进行的</a>。投诉显示，一名公司代表告诉该机构，该标志是为一次活动临时设置的。</p><p> X 没有评论为什么该标志被移除。</p><p>这是自 7 月宣布品牌重塑以来，马斯克对这家社交媒体公司的名称、标识和装饰进行快速改革的最新举措。这也是一周内第二次该市和 X 就该建筑的标牌发生冲突，这象征着一次突然的品牌重塑，并引起<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musks-pivot-to-x-draws-strong-opinions-across-twitter-5bc80833?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">了不同的反应</a>。</p><p>一周前，工人们开始拆除公司总部大楼外的 Twitter 标牌。这引起了旧金山警方的密切关注，他们表示正在调查街道是否被不当封锁，但最终表示没有发生任何犯罪行为。</p><p>该市建筑检查部门表示，X标志是在没有许可证的情况下竖立的，这使得该建筑不安全，业主将必须支付包括许可费和市政府调查费用在内的费用。</p><p>该市表示，该标志牌也在未经许可的情况下被拆除，但出于安全考虑，拆除标志牌后可以获得许可证。</p><p>该标志的拆除集中体现了去年收购该平台的马斯克与旧金山之间的紧张关系。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amid-san-franciscos-woes-elon-musk-plays-critic-fa98ab18?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">马斯克多次批评</a>市中心的状况，在一条推文中将其描述为“后世界末日”。</p><p>尽管有抱怨，马斯克周末还是表示 X 不会离开这座城市。他在推特上写道：“旧金山，美丽的旧金山，尽管别人抛弃了你，我们永远是你的朋友。”</p><p>写信给 Lindsey Choo，邮箱： <a href="mailto:lindsey.choo@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">lindsey.choo@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 01:06:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/x-sign-removed-from-top-of-former-twitter-hq-59f5a9f0</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/x-sign-removed-from-top-of-former-twitter-hq-59f5a9f0<author><![CDATA[Lindsey Choo]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>裁员/裁员</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>裁员</category><category>裁员</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Real-Estate Deal Gone Bad Hits Popular Crowd Funder]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> CrowdStreet 通过向小投资者承诺巨额回报筹集了 40 亿美元，但许多交易令人失望<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825172/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="涉及亚特兰大金融中心的交易是 CrowdStreet 有史以来规模最大的交易之一。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>涉及亚特兰大金融中心的交易是 CrowdStreet 有史以来规模最大的交易之一。安德烈·珍妮/阿拉米<span>安德烈·珍妮/阿拉米</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001091011"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001091011"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/shane-shifflett" itemprop="url" rel="author">肖恩·希夫莱特</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ben-foldy" itemprop="url" rel="author">本·福迪</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 31 日下午 6:01（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/missing-millions-and-a-rabbinical-arbitrator-real-estate-deal-gone-bad-hits-popular-crowd-funder-3555314f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>承诺让小投资者参与大型房地产项目的最大平台之一错过了危险信号，并将资金注入捏造过去的公司。现在，该公司面临着交易失败的问题，6300 万美元的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/atlantas-record-62-million-crowdfunding-deal-raises-red-flags-with-some-investors-11661266801?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">客户现金</a>失踪。</p><p> CrowdStreet 通过宣扬丰厚回报为房地产开发商筹集了 40 亿美元，但许多交易都未能实现。</p><p>周一这篇报道发表后，CrowdStreet 表示将更换首席执行官。</p><p>失败的交易涉及一家名为南丁格尔地产（Nightingale Properties）的房地产开发商，该公司筹集资金购买亚特兰大和迈阿密的办公楼。在本月提交的破产申请中，新任命的项目首席重组官声称，这些建筑从未被购买，除了 127,000 美元之外，投资者的资金全部转移到其他账户，其中一些账户属于南丁格尔首席执行官。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="1000" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825518?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>尽管存在一些潜在的危险信号，CrowdStreet 仍在推广 Nightingale 产品。该开发商在向投资者展示的业绩记录中省略了两笔糟糕交易的结果。交易运营协议中的仲裁条款规定，争议将由拉比法庭解决。</p><p>南丁格尔的律师及其首席执行官埃利·施瓦茨拒绝置评。被替换的 CrowdStreet 首席执行官托雷·斯蒂恩 (Tore Steen) 上周拒绝回答他的公司是否对丢失的资金负有任何责任，他表示，“CrowdStreet 没有在这里实施欺诈行为。” The RealDeal 早些时候报道了斯蒂恩的离职。</p><p> CrowdStreet 是小型投资者联合购买办公楼、酒店和其他类型商业房地产的多个平台中最大的平台之一。开发商通过网络广播向投资者进行推介，同时 CrowdStreet 代表介入宣布“立即投资”按钮何时被激活。</p><p>开发商支付费用来宣传他们的交易，投资者可以以低至 25,000 美元的价格购买少量股权。超过 770 笔交易的赞助商已在该平台上筹集了超过 40 亿美元。<br><br> 《华尔街日报》对 104 笔已完成的交易以及其他已中止或仍在进行中的交易进行的审查发现，许多交易未能达到销售宣传中建议的回报。当开发商资金短缺时，他们会要求投资者支付更多现金，否则将面临失去投资的风险。据美国证券交易委员会和司法部称，CrowdStreet 还帮助一家向投资者谎报业绩记录的公司筹集现金，该公司首席执行官后来因融资欺诈被判入狱。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=88CDF171-D046-4FD4-A4BB-72130DCCB4C6&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fmissing-millions-and-a-rabbinical-arbitrator-real-estate-deal-gone-bad-hits-popular-crowd-funder-3555314f&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">由于住房供应短缺，开发商正在将更多空置办公室改造成公寓。但并非所有建筑物都适合重复利用，尽管美国各地有超过 10 亿平方英尺的办公空间闲置 图片插图：Amber Bragdon<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>《华尔街日报》分析了该公司从 2013 年到 2022 年 8 月发布的 104 笔已完成的财产出售或投资者赎回交易的预期和实现回报数据。</p><p> 《华尔街日报》分析发现，CrowdStreet 平台上推广的投资中有一半以上未能达到目标回报。据《华尔街日报》分析，截至今年 7 月，数百名 CrowdStreet 用户在 19 笔表现不佳的交易中损失了约 3400 万美元。其中十几笔交易损失了近 100% 的投资者资金。</p><p> CrowdStreet 也举办了成功的交易。超过 20 笔交易的回报率超出预期至少 10 个百分点。还有数百人仍然悬而未决。投资者通常需要至少三年的时间才能实现投资回报。</p><p>该平台的一位发言人表示，该公司看到的交易实现的回报高于或低于预期，并为投资者创造了 3.07 亿美元的利润。</p><p>由于供应短缺、价格上涨或利率上升，一些开发商遇到了意想不到的成本或低估了他们的现金需求。</p><p> 2020 年至 2021 年间，Fountain Residential Partners 在 CrowdStreet 上筹集了 4500 万美元，用于克莱姆森大学、阿肯色大学和路易斯安那州立大学的三个校外学生住房项目，其中一个需要大修，另一个基本上无法居住<strong>&nbsp;</strong>洪水发生后几个月。</p><p>由于成本超支，Fountain 向 CrowdStreet 投资者追加 1,240 万美元，并于 9 月份被告知预计将再筹集数百万美元。</p><p> “看来我们还需要 2000 万美元才能完成该项目，”Fountain 首席执行官布伦特·利特尔 (Brent Little) 在 9 月份的阿肯色州项目网络研讨会上说道。利特尔将超支归咎于疫情期间<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sky-high-lumber-prices-are-back-11639842879?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">木材价格</a>上涨等材料价格。该公司几个月来都没有透露需要更多资金来完成修复，因为“我们认为这会引发不必要的恐慌，”他说。</p><p>利特尔拒绝发表评论。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="503" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825194?width=700&amp;height=503" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2020 年至 2021 年间，为克莱姆森大学和其他学校的校外学生住宿项目筹集了数百万美元。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：肯·鲁纳德/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>CrowdStreet 的营销材料对房地产回报做出了乐观的假设。在该公司运营的私人房地产投资信托基金的宣传中，该公司表示，从历史上看，较高的利率会增加房地产价值。格林街商业地产价格指数显示，随着利率上升，房产价值通常会下降，自美联储去年开始加息以来，房产价值已经下降了 15%。</p><p> 2018 年，MG Capital Management 向 CrowdStreet 投资者推出了一只新基金，该公司自称是“曼哈顿最大的无债务个人豪华房产业主兼管理者”。 CrowdStreet 的首席投资官当时谈到 MG 时表示：“我们专门与领先的赞助商合作提供商业房地产产品，以满足我们严格的市场要求。”<br><br> MG Capital 的发行材料称，该公司监管的两只基金在 10 年内的回报率是标准普尔 500 指数的四倍。该公司表示，新基金的投资者“100%免受损失”。 MG Capital 从 CrowdStreet 投资者那里筹集了 180 万美元，该基金筹集的资金总额为 3500 万美元。据 CrowdStreet 称，参与此次交易的 23 名投资者收回了约三分之一的资金。<br><br> 2021年，美国证券交易委员会和司法部指控MG Capital及其经理犯有证券欺诈罪。政府表示，MG Capital 的基金伪造报告以掩盖巨额损失，其之前的基金根本不存在。 MG Capital 首席执行官承认融资证券欺诈罪，被判处 60 个月监禁，MG Capital 与 SEC 达成和解。</p><p> Nightingale 收购亚特兰大金融中心的交易是 CrowdStreet 有史以来规模最大的交易之一。潜在投资者收到了 CrowdStreet 首席投资官发来的电子邮件，主题为：“100 亿美元的企业赞助商在热门市场带来了具有巨大潜力的奖杯资产。” Nightingale 从 654 名 CrowdStreet 投资者那里筹集了约 5400 万美元，用于在亚特兰大巴克海特社区建造一座闪闪发光的玻璃覆盖办公楼。开发商还为迈阿密的一座建筑筹集了约 800 万美元。</p><p> CrowdStreet 将南丁格尔评为最高级别的“企业”赞助商，表明其业务遍及全国，投资组合价值超过 50 亿美元。此次上市预计内部回报率为28.1%，是该平台项目中最高的。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825196?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> MG Capital 将自己描述为曼哈顿最大的无债务个人豪华房产业主兼管理者。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：AMR ALFIKY/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>去年夏天，路易斯安那州的神经科学家彼得·坎贝尔 (Peter Campbell) 在这笔交易中投入了 10 万美元，他说：“所有这些因素共同作用，引发了围绕这项投资的狂热。”<br><br> Nightingale 向 CrowdStreet 支付了使用其市场的费用，并计划在交易完成后向其支付超过 210 万美元。<br><br>去年夏天，《华尔街日报》报道称，一些投资者在发现南丁格尔遗漏了前一年向贷方损失一栋大楼以及拖欠投资者资料 2500 万美元后，对这项投资产生了不满。当时，CrowdStreet 的一位发言人表示，这些遗漏是良性的、无关紧要的，如果投资者愿意，他们可以退还资金。</p><p> CrowdStreet 的 Steen 在上周接受《华尔街日报》采访时表示，该公司在其流程中分析了未公开的交易，但认为违约或取消抵押品赎回权不应阻止开发商在该平台上上市。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> CrowdStreet 允许投资者在 2 月份之前为该交易提供资金，但一些人表示，他们开始要求 CrowdStreet 和 Nightingale 退还资金。坎贝尔表示，他向南丁格尔公司高管发送了 11 封电子邮件并召开了电话会议，之后他的资金才于 6 月份返还。<br><br>丹尼斯·格卢什科夫从三月份开始要求他提供资金。 CrowdStreet 告诉他，Nightingale 会尊重退款请求，但第二天，Nightingale 在一封电子邮件中告诉他，“目前不考虑任何赎回”，因为它试图完成该建筑的交易。</p><p>格卢什科夫五月份被告知，他已被添加到即将赎回的名单中，但从未拿到钱。该公司持有投资者现金，并于 7 月 14 日在特拉华州根据美国破产法第 11 章申请破产保护。<br><br>当天晚些时候，被任命为该工具受托人的安娜·菲利普斯 (Anna Phillips) 告诉投资者，财务记录显示，在从投资者那里筹集资金后不久，数百万美元就已转移给施瓦茨及其关联公司。投资者的资金只剩下 127,000 美元。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您对 CrowdStreet 等众筹平台有何看法？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>菲利普斯表示，交易存在“大量存在欺诈迹象的危险信号”，但她表示，她需要直接与施瓦茨交谈并收集更多事实，然后才能做出决定。<br><br>这笔钱并不像房地产交易中常见的那样存入托管账户。 CrowdStreet 从六月开始使用此类帐户。斯蒂恩表示，该公司也在改变其商业模式，不再是一个为投资者与试图筹集资金的公司牵线搭桥的市场。它将成为一家注册经纪交易商，就像大多数出售投资的公司一样。</p><p>格卢什科夫表示，CrowdStreet 很容易成为欺诈目标，他对 CrowdStreet 没有采取更多措施保护投资者现金感到震惊。</p><p> “如果你决定窃取 7000 万美元，我相信如果是高盛的，他们会三思而后行，”他说。 “当你的投资基础小而分散时，你就更容易想到，‘我要挪用这些资金，祝他们好运。’”</p><p>写信给 Shane Shifflett <a href="mailto:shane.shifflett@dowjones.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（shane.shifflett@dowjones.com）</a>和 Ben Foldy（ <a href="mailto:ben.foldy@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ben.foldy@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 22:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/missing-millions-and-a-rabbinical-仲裁员-real-estate-deal-gone-bad-hits-popular-crowd-funder-3555314f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/missing-millions-and-a-rabbinical-仲裁员-real-estate-deal-gone-bad-hits-popular-crowd-funder-3555314f<author><![CDATA[Shane ShifflettBen Foldy]]></author><category>华尔街日报财经</category><category>专有的</category><category>企业融资</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>众筹</category><category>中小型企业</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>布伦特·利特尔</category><category>企业融资</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>众筹</category><category>小的</category><category>中型企业</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Catering to Your Midlife Crisis Is a Growing Business]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>新兴行业帮助那些寻求充实的第二幕的成年人<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086694"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824308?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">寿命的延长导致更多的人在 40 多岁、50 多岁和 60 多岁时寻找有意义的追求。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：iStock </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086694"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/anne-tergesen" itemprop="url" rel="author">安妮·特格森</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 31 日上午 10:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/midlife-crisis-money-business-companies-29dc2273"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>美国人希望他们的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-virtuous-midlife-crisis-11578830400?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">中年危机</a>变得更有成效。这为越来越多的公司、教练和顾问提供了数百万美元的机会。</p><p>有些程序是在线的，收费几百美元。其他活动则在异国情调的地点进行，提供豪华住宿、瑜伽和冲浪课程，费用为数千美元。有时会有折扣。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/death-finances-and-how-many-of-us-get-our-money-needs-wrong-51a660a2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">更长的寿命</a>为企业提供了动力，引导更多的人在 40 多岁、50 多岁和 60 多岁时寻找有意义的追求。一些心理学家将这一时期称为第二次成年期，在此期间，从行政人员到全职父母再到照顾者等身份塑造角色可能会消失，导致一些人重新评估。</p><p>现代老年学院（MEA）联合创始人奇普·康利（Chip Conley）表示：“在这个寿命越来越长、变化越来越大的时代，过渡是我们需要掌握的一项技能。”该学院提供在线和面对面的研讨会。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824307?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">现代老年学院联合创始人奇普·康利 (Chip Conley) 身穿白衬衫，他表示，年龄歧视会让中年人认为自己无关紧要。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：现代长者学院</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>一些研究表明，生活满意度在 40 多岁左右达到低点，这可能是因为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/work-life-balance-is-their-second-priority-work-is-their-first-b069aeee?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">工作和家庭需求</a>带来的压力。这种权衡，加上<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/would-life-be-better-if-you-worked-less-3f49e69a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">很少的时间进行自我反思</a>，让许多人不确定如何迎接他们的下一个篇章。</p><p>康利说，中年课程的讲师探讨的主题包括中年心理发展和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/anti-ageism-workplace-language-biggest-school-district-368db30f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">年龄歧视</a>，这可能会让人们相信自己“无关紧要，已经过时了，最好的时光已经过去了”。</p><p>他在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ABNB" class="">Airbnb</a>工作后创建了 MEA <span class="company-name-type">，</span>这家家庭共享公司的年轻创始人称他为现代长者，52 岁。研讨会旨在帮助参与者学习更好地应对压力过渡， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/layoffs-tech-job-cuts-fired-survival-guide-how-to-get-hired-laid-off-employees-11667943893?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">包括裁员</a>、离婚和亲人去世。</p><h3>自我反思的空间</h3><p>与一些大学<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/for-60-000-these-colleges-help-older-workers-plot-encore-careers-a0060b9a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">为接近职业生涯结束的成年人</a>推出的为期数月的学术课程一样，大多数中年课程都以 8 到 50 人为一组。</p><p> “这些项目为人们提供了空间和结构，不仅可以考虑他们在这个阶段想做什么，还可以考虑成为谁，”芭芭拉·瓦克斯曼说，</p>一位在 MEA 任教的老年学家。<p></p><p> 46 岁的纳迪亚·阿尔·亚法伊 (Nadia Al Yafai) 表示，她最近从一家英国保险公司的高级职位被解雇后，发现了 Midlife ReThink，这是一个价值 385 美元的在线计划。</p><p>她说，“中年反思”被证明具有变革性，并补充说，遇到其他同样感到无依无靠的人让她感到安慰。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824305?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Midlife ReThink 为寻求新方向的人们提供在线课程，其中一张幻灯片概述了人生的各个阶段。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：中年反思</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>该计划由专门研究劳动力性别和代际平衡的教练兼顾问 Avivah Wittenberg-Cox 于 2020 年发起，包括三个 90 分钟的在线课程，约有 25 名参与者。</p><p> “很多人都在经历自己的转变，就好像他们正在经历一些可怕的事情一样，”维滕伯格-考克斯说。她说，“社区是帮助人们认识到在这个年龄和阶段变得焦躁不安是正常的、可以预见的”并渴望改变的关键。</p><p> Al Yafai 表示，一项要求她定义未来七年想要什么的练习促使她开始了咨询业务。</p><p> “我从因不再是旧世界的一部分而感到有点失落，到意识到有一个新世界，人们在做真正有趣的事情，”她说。</p><h3> “我们仍然有价值”</h3><p> Reboot Partners 提供职业和其他转型方面的研讨会和辅导，今年在新墨西哥州圣达菲和纽约州萨格港组织了两次为期周末的静修活动，费用为 1,895 美元。联合创始人杰耶·史密斯 (Jaye Smith) 表示，参与者想象自己的完美生活，并讨论对变革的恐惧和动机。 </p><p></p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824304?width=700&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">现代老年学院在墨西哥校园举办的虚拟和现场研讨会旨在帮助参与者更好地应对压力过渡。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：现代长者学院</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>On an oceanfront campus in Mexico&#39;s Baja California Sur, MEA teaches courses on re-creating careers, embracing midlife and optimizing longevity. It also offers weekslong online programs on transitions, purpose and reframing retirement for $395 to $1,250. It plans to open a campus in Santa Fe, NM, next year.</p><p> Lisa Fitzpatrick said MEA, which she first attended in 2019, helped her face down barriers to success.</p><p> Dr. Fitzpatrick, 55, was launching Grapevine Health, which publishes online health information for low-income communities. She relished the opportunity to interact with Conley, a veteran entrepreneur.</p><p> The Washington, DC, resident said an exercise to identify self-limiting beliefs helped her conquer a fear of being too old to start a business. She returned to Baja five times to attend workshops on entrepreneurship and healthcare. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="959" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824306?width=639&amp;height=959" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Lisa Fitzpatrick says attending Modern Elder Academy helped her confront her barriers to success.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ron Ceaser</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> For that first visit, she received a scholarship for a seven-day stay that now costs $4,000 to $5,500.</p><p> One exercise Fitzpatrick particularly enjoys involves stacking rocks on the beach. “It sounds kind of woo-woo,” she said. But the task of balancing a big rock on a small one helped her overcome mental barriers to what she could achieve. “MEA helps people in midlife realize we still have value,” she said.</p><h3> Finding a purpose</h3><p> Some programs explore next acts or spirituality.</p><p> Dallas-based Halftime Institute&#39;s offerings include a two-day, $2,500 couples retreat and a $25,000 yearlong program. The latter features in-person and online sessions, as well as one-on-one coaching on relationships, health, faith and finding one&#39;s calling.</p><p> “Not everyone who goes through it is Christian but that&#39;s the perspective we come from,” said Co-Chief Executive Jim Stollberg. “We talk about a calling, rather than a purpose.”</p><p> For $2,500, Union Theological Seminary in New York offers a four-month Encore Transition program, with virtual sessions on topics such as spirituality in midlife and finding work with social purpose.</p><p> Consultant Carolyn Buck Luce leads a group of women through a weekslong online program called the Decade Game that costs $2,250. It challenges participants to set goals to guide their next decade in areas including education and purpose.</p><p> “It&#39;s about being able to declare the purpose you were called to,” said Luce.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>How are you navigating midlife?加入下面的对话。</em> </p></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/b28e0b44-8140-466a-922c-df1aa6d8aa70.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Write to Anne Tergesen at <a href="mailto:anne.tergesen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">anne.tergesen@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/midlife-crisis-money-business-companies-29dc2273</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/midlife-crisis-money-business-companies-29dc2273<author><![CDATA[Anne Tergesen]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Career Planning/Management</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>Retirement Planning</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>career planning</category><category>管理</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>retirement planning </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[New Ultrasound Therapy Could Help Treat Alzheimer’s, Cancer]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Sound waves combined with tiny bubbles in the bloodstream can push drugs into the brain and tough-to-reach tumors <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825729/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="French company Carthera has developed an ultrasound device to treat brain cancer. Shown here in a rendering, it works with tiny bubbles injected into the bloodstream to help drugs penetrate where they are needed." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> French company Carthera has developed an ultrasound device to treat brain cancer. Shown here in a rendering, it works with tiny bubbles injected into the bloodstream to help drugs penetrate where they are needed. Carthera <span>Carthera</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001068286"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001068286"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/denise-roland" itemprop="url" rel="author">Denise Roland</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 31, 2023 9:50 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ultrasound-therapy-alzheimers-cancer-treatment-862f1390"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Ultrasound, the decades-old technology known for giving early glimpses of unborn babies, could hold a key to a problem that has long challenged drug developers: getting medicines to hard-to-reach places to treat diseases like Alzheimer&#39;s and cancer.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> A cutting-edge approach that combines ultrasound waves with tiny bubbles of inert gas injected into the bloodstream can get more chemotherapy to tumor cells and enable drugs to breach one of the most stubborn frontiers in the human body—the blood-brain barrier. It is also being explored as a new way to deliver gene therapy.</p><p> “There&#39;s an extremely wide variety of where this sort of drug delivery or augmentation with ultrasound and bubbles can take us,” says Flemming Forsberg, professor of radiology and director of ultrasound physics at Thomas Jefferson University in Philadelphia. The effectiveness of drugs in treating diseases like cancer, Alzheimer&#39;s and Parkinson&#39;s is often limited by poor penetration into tissues, he says, whether in the brain or in tumors in other parts of the body.</p><h3> Getting Medicine to the Site</h3><p> To get to the places they are needed, many drugs must move from the bloodstream into surrounding tissue. The medicines have to travel through the thin walls of the capillaries, the body&#39;s smallest blood vessels, and reach the target cells. This is tougher in some parts of the body than others. Some tumors are surrounded by dense networks of connective tissue that are hard to penetrate. In the brain, the capillary-wall cells are so tightly packed that they form a barrier that the vast majority of drugs can&#39;t get through.</p><p> The new approach relies on targeted ultrasound waves that cause vibrations in tiny bubbles that are injected into the bloodstream. The resulting force—which some compare to the way an opera singer&#39;s voice can make a wine glass quiver and even shatter—disrupts the surrounding capillary walls and tissue, temporarily creating microscopic gaps that have been shown to ease the passage of drugs in early human studies. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825973?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Carthera&#39;s ultrasound-emitting device for the brain is embedded in titanium mesh.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Carthera</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Some key questions must be explored as research progresses into larger human studies, says Seung-Schik Yoo, a researcher at Brigham and Women&#39;s Hospital and associate professor of radiology at Harvard Medical School who has done work in this area. One is ensuring that the disruption doesn&#39;t cause any lasting damage to tissues. Another is figuring out how frequently the procedure can be applied—and if there is a limit to the number of applications.</p><p> The procedure takes place during drug dosing or soon after. Typically, the microbubbles are injected intravenously while ultrasound, similar to the type used for fetal imaging, is applied at the target site for around five minutes. In one cancer trial, for instance, the microbubbles and ultrasound are administered around an hour after chemotherapy begins, so that the drug is at a high concentration in the blood at the time of the procedure.</p><p> While the microbubbles flow throughout the bloodstream, the disruption in tissue only occurs in the part of the body exposed to the ultrasound wave. The effect is temporary, lasting for as little as an hour, and the microbubbles remain in the blood for only around five minutes. The tiny size of the bubbles means they don&#39;t pose a risk of causing dangerous blockages in blood vessels, researchers say.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> EXPLORE THE FUTURE OF EVERYTHING</h4><p> <em>The Future of Everything looks at the innovation and technology transforming the way we live, work and play, covering <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/whats-ahead-for-work-bd3a352d" target="_blank" class="icon none">the workplace</a> , <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/whats-ahead-for-health-5dccbfca" target="_blank" class="icon none">health</a> , <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/whats-ahead-for-energy-climate-19d48267" target="_blank" class="icon none">energy &amp; climate</a> and more.</em></p></div></div><p> The component technologies aren&#39;t new. Ultrasound has been used in medicine for more than half a century. Since the 1990s, microbubbles injected into the bloodstream have been widely used as a contrast agent to enhance images created by diagnostic ultrasound.</p><p> Scientists observed that ultrasound causes these bubbles to resonate and saw the potential for that force to aid drug delivery. In 2001, scientists at Harvard Medical School demonstrated that ultrasound plus microbubbles could <a href="https://pubs.rsna.org/doi/10.1148/radiol.2202001804" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">open the blood-brain barrier in rabbits</a> . In the years since, scientists have tested the approach in many types of animals, building up early evidence that it could boost drug uptake and lead to meaningful improvements like greater tumor shrinkage in cancer.</p><h3> Treatment for Brain Cancer</h3><p> Now early human trials are producing encouraging results. In a small <a href="https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lanonc/article/PIIS1470-2045(23)00112-2/fulltext" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">study of patients with glioblastoma</a> —a type of brain cancer—researchers found that using the technology in treatment with carboplatin, a powerful chemotherapy, resulted in six times the amount of the drug in brain tissue that was exposed to the targeted ultrasound compared with unexposed brain tissue. In patients treated with paclitaxel, another cancer drug, levels were 3.7 times higher where the procedure was applied. Under normal circumstances, both drugs are seldom used to treat brain cancer because so little can get across the blood-brain barrier, according to Adam Sonabend, associate professor of neurological surgery at Northwestern University, who was involved in the trial.</p><p> In the glioblastoma trial, a small device developed by French company Carthera was used to avoid the difficulty of passing ultrasound through the skull bone, which weakens the power of the sound waves, according to the company&#39;s chief scientific officer Michael Canney. The ultrasound emitting device is embedded in titanium mesh used to reconstruct a small gap in the skull after surgery to remove the tumor, and sits directly above the brain. It emits ultrasound waves when connected to a power source via a syringe-like mechanism. The bubbles and the drugs are injected into the arm by intravenous infusion.</p><p> Exact Therapeutics, a Norwegian company, recently told investors that liver tumors in two patients in a Phase 1 clinical trial that were exposed to ultrasound plus microbubbles during chemotherapy shrank more than those without the ultrasound. The trial is still under way at the Royal Marsden Hospital in London, and the results haven&#39;t yet been peer-reviewed.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Have you or friends and family encountered medical advances in treatment of disease? What was your experience?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> The company has developed a formulation of microbubbles mixed with tiny oil droplets. When exposed to a particular frequency of ultrasound, they combine to temporarily form slightly larger bubbles in capillaries near the target tissue. They press directly against the capillary walls and stay there for longer, strengthening and prolonging the disruptive effects that allow drugs to pass into the target tissue, according to Exact Therapeutics Chief Executive Per Walday.</p><h3> Avenue for Gene Therapy </h3><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825974?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> San Francisco-based SonoThera is developing a technology that uses microbubbles and ultrasound to deliver gene therapies.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: SonoThera</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Another potential application of the new ultrasound approach is in gene therapy. Now, gene therapies rely on stripped-down viruses to carry and insert genetic material into target cells. A shortcoming of that approach is that the virus generates an immune response, so any repeat dose would be quickly destroyed by the body&#39;s defenses. Another limitation of viral vectors is that they can only carry genes up to a certain size. Animal studies suggest that ultrasound plus microbubbles could enable genetic material to pass into target cells without a viral carrier. San Francisco-based startup SonoThera is developing the technology with the aim of starting a Phase 1 clinical trial in 2025, the company&#39;s Chief Executive Kenneth Greenberg says.</p><p> An important area of work has been fine-tuning the size and shape of the ultrasound waves to bring about the right level of vibration for the target tissue in question, Greenberg says. “Much like a symphony, there is a complexity of different sounds and harmonics and amplitudes and timing that can be delivered through ultrasound,” he says. “The new twist is how you optimize the acoustics to maximize delivery for specific target organs.”</p><p> Ultrasound research could open up many new opportunities, say those involved. “This is just the beginning,” says Carthera&#39;s Canney. With this technology, he says, doctors can revisit many drugs that have performed poorly in the past and ask: “Is it the drug, or just that we&#39;re not getting the drug there?”</p><p> Write to <a href="mailto:future@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">future@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/d0225ea7-8532-42a1-8c31-5b317282b95d.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 13:50:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ultrasound-therapy-alzheimers-cancer-treatment-862f1390</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ultrasound-therapy-alzheimers-cancer-treatment-862f1390<author><![CDATA[Denise Roland]]></author><category> wsj future of everything</category><category> Pharmaceuticals</category><category> Cancer Drugs</category><category> Healthcare/Life Sciences</category><category> Specialized Drugs/Medications</category><category> Cancer</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Chemotherapy/Radiotherapy/Immunotherapy</category><category> Demographic Health</category><category>健康</category><category>Infant/Child/Teenage Health</category><category> Medical Conditions</category><category> Medical Treatments/Procedures</category><category> WSJ Future of Everything</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> cancer</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>chemotherapy</category><category> radiotherapy</category><category> immunotherapy</category><category> demographic health</category><category>健康</category><category>婴儿</category><category>孩子</category><category>teenage health</category><category> medical conditions</category><category> medical treatments</category><category>程序</category><category>pharmaceuticals</category><category> cancer drugs</category><category> healthcare</category><category> life sciences</category><category> specialized drugs</category><category>药物</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Hollywood’s Fight: How Much AI Is Too Much?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Studios see potential in the technology, while actors, writers and other industry workers fear the worst <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826143/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Photo Illustration by Emil Lendof/The Wall Street Journal <span>Photo Illustration by Emil Lendof/The Wall Street Journal</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001095061"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001095061"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jessica-toonkel" itemprop="url" rel="author">Jessica Toonkel</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/amol-sharma" itemprop="url" rel="author">Amol Sharma</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 31, 2023 7:56 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/at-the-core-of-hollywoods-ai-fight-how-far-is-too-far-f57630df"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Alan Ruck, the actor who played Connor Roy in HBO&#39;s “Succession,” says he and a director friend tested out the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chatgpt-ai-chatbot-app-explained-11675865177?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">generative-AI tool ChatGPT</a> a few months ago over lunch, to see whether it could write a screenplay.</p><p> They asked it to write a scene about Ruck as a soldier in basic training, a play on the actor&#39;s role in the Broadway show “Biloxi Blues.”</p><p> “It was s <em>—</em> ,” Ruck said. “It was every cliché and hackneyed idea you could imagine.”</p><p> The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/podcasts/tech-news-briefing/ai-and-streaming-play-leading-roles-in-hollywood-strike/e0fbf61f-eaf4-41b4-b2a5-1f2f184c5636?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">potential use of artificial intelligence</a> in TV and movies has become a hot-button issue in the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hollywood-actors-set-to-join-writers-on-strike-after-contract-expires-d86e7f30?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">biggest Hollywood labor strike</a> in 60 years. Ruck, like many writers and actors on the picket lines, is worried the technology will replace jobs and produce low-quality content.</p><p> Entertainment executives say bots won&#39;t be penning scripts soon, calling such fears overblown. But big companies across Hollywood, including <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WBD" class="">Warner Bros. Discovery</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PARA" class="company-name">Paramount Global</a> and NBCUniversal, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-chatgpt-hollywood-intellectual-property-spongebob-81fd5d15?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">are already using AI tools</a> in other ways and are actively exploring new applications, from summarizing scripts to special-effects to promotional marketing, people familiar with the situation say. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826209?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Alan Ruck, who is seen in a scene from HBO&#39;s &#39;Succession,&#39; has raised concerns over AI tools.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: HBO/Everett Collection</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Several studio executives said AI tools could accelerate storyboarding, which uses a series of graphics to show how a story unfolds, and set design <strong>,</strong> such as dreaming up what a restaurant in the 1960s might look like. Producers could use <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-deepfakes-celebrity-marketing-brands-81381aa6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a digital replica</a> of an actor to make tweaks to a scene without having to reshoot it—to turn someone&#39;s head or change their expression slightly, studio executives said.</p><p> A promising application is for dubbing of actors&#39; voices in different languages. AI could make the audio sound like Ben Affleck or Harrison Ford in Italian or German and even adjust the movement of their lips accordingly.</p><p> Some production workers say this is all leading down a dangerous path. Harry Yoon, a film editor who has worked on such movies as “Minari” and “Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings,” said he is worried that AI models, if fed enough data, could create a decent first cut of a scene.</p><p> “Pretty soon executives will be asking, &#39;Why do we need three editors on a series? Why not two or one?&#39;” he said. Yoon said there is a value in the slow process of humans watching daily footage and hearing lines over and over. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=0B69A51F-2148-4479-9D5B-1AB9ABE390DC&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fat-the-core-of-hollywoods-ai-fight-how-far-is-too-far-f57630df&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Netflix co-Chief Executive Ted Sarandos said the company and other streaming platforms, studios and networks were &#39;super committed&#39; to reaching a deal with striking Hollywood actors and writers. Photo: Chris Delmas/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Entertainment giants have talked to a range of AI players, including OpenAI, text-to-video specialist Runway, image-generator Stability Diffusion and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ADBE" class="">Adobe</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span></p> as they explore how to put the technology to use. Entertainment executives say some jobs probably would be at risk as AI is woven into the production process, but in other cases it would just be a tool to make jobs easier.<p></p><p> “AI raises hard, important creative and legal questions for everyone,” said the Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers, the group that negotiates on behalf of studios and streamers. “So it&#39;s something that requires a lot more discussion, which we&#39;re committed to doing.”</p><p> Warner has held discussions with OpenAI about using ChatGPT for tasks such as creating descriptions of shows on its Max streaming service and possibly, down the road, for summarizing scripts submitted to studio executives for review, according to people familiar with the situation.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NFLX" class="company-name">Netflix</a></p> is looking to hire an AI product manager who will “define the strategic vision for” the streamer&#39;s machine-learning platform, according to a job posting.<p></p><p> The labor unions involved in the strike—the Screen Actors Guild and Writers Guild of America— <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fran-drescher-nanny-actors-strike-sag-aftra-4477c7cd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">are pushing for better compensation</a> in the streaming era and to shore up their benefits. But they are also pushing for protections from the rise of AI tools.</p><p> “It isn&#39;t just a danger for creative labor in Hollywood. It&#39;s a danger for all labor everywhere,” said Ruck, who has been out on the picket lines. “If they can program AI to replace the creative jobs they will certainly be able to program it to replace middle-management jobs.”</p><p> AI company executives say the point of their tools isn&#39;t to replace creators, but to allow them to have more time doing the creative parts of their jobs. “We only hear horror stories and fairy tales,” said Cristóbal Valenzuela, chief executive of Runway. “It&#39;s much more nuanced than that…you can&#39;t just type in &#39;make me a movie,&#39; and it will create a movie.”</p><p> Chad Nelson, chief creative director at Topgolf Media, who recently created a short film with OpenAI&#39;s DALL-E tool, predicted AI tools will be replacing some creative jobs in Hollywood within one to two years. “The idea that you need to secure a drone shot on the Pacific Coast Highway at sunset with a specific color car and the light in a certain way, won&#39;t be a thing people will have to do anymore,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="394" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826210?width=700&amp;height=394" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> AI tools were used for work on the film &#39;Everything Everywhere All at Once,&#39; which stars Michelle Yeoh.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: David Bornfriend/A24/Everett Collection</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Evan Halleck, a visual-effects specialist who used Runway&#39;s tools to work on the Oscar-winning film “Everything Everywhere All at Once,” said he loves that these tools allowed him to reduce some of the more tedious work in his job. However, he said, “I have fears that a 10-day gig might become a five-day gig.”</p><p> AI tools already can handle some work done by concept designers, who are hired by studios to help illustrate a scene. “The thing that sucks about the visual-effects industry as opposed to writers or actors is we don&#39;t have a union,” said Bilali Mack, a visual-effects supervisor who recently worked with Brendan Fraser on the Oscar-winning movie, “The Whale.”</p><p> Mark Patch, a former visual-effects production worker, said he is trying to organize people in a union for entertainment industry workers.</p><p> The Motion Pictures Editors Guild is addressing AI and how it could affect its members in a coming report, according to a letter the group sent to its members earlier in July.</p><p> The Screen Actors Guild says it wants to ensure studios obtain “informed consent” from actors before using digital replicas of them, and offer talent fair compensation. The Writers Guild of America has said it wants to clearly define that “source material” and “literary material,” which its members get compensated for, cannot be generated by AI tools. The Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers has said it has made robust and fair proposals addressing those concerns.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What role should AI play in the entertainment industry?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> To address the issue of consent, a startup called Vaisual is creating databases of actors who have given the company permission to have their photos taken and be part of its AI model.</p><p> Entertainment executives said they would be open to writers using AI technologies as a tool to help them brainstorm and develop stories, but the idea of bots replacing human writers is far-fetched.</p><p> “Generative AI can generate a lot of ideas but it can&#39;t tell the difference between a good idea and a bad idea,” said Jon Dudkowski, a director of the Paramount+ series “Star Trek: Discovery.”</p><p> Some actors and writers are worried that if they don&#39;t take a hard line now on AI, when it is in its infancy, it will be too late.</p><p> “The AI technology we have right now is the worst it will ever be in our lifetimes, which is why it&#39;s important right now to define if it is its own creative entity or whether it&#39;s a tool for creatives to use,” said producer and writer Dahlia Heyman, who <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/streaming-brought-hollywood-to-a-standstill-now-comes-the-pain-3afcbb68?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">was picketing at Netflix</a> on a recent afternoon.</p><p> Leif Gantvoort, an actor who has worked on shows such as “NCIS” and “SWAT,” said he is more concerned about compensation issues than AI. “That is a wave that&#39;s on its way,” he said. “To stand in its way—I just don&#39;t see it as the primary concern.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826212?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The potential use of AI in TV and movies has become a hot-button issue in the biggest Hollywood labor strike in 60 years.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: caroline brehman/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p class="articleTagLine"> —Tom Dotan contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Jessica Toonkel at <a href="mailto:jessica.toonkel@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jessica.toonkel@wsj.com</a> and Amol Sharma at <a href="mailto:Amol.Sharma@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Amol.Sharma@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/45b711d0-d12b-4ed4-89ff-24783c6b1fa4.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 11:56:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/at-the-core-of-hollywoods-ai-fight-how-far-is-too-far-f57630df</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/at-the-core-of-hollywoods-ai-fight-how-far-is-too-far-f57630df<author><![CDATA[Jessica ToonkelAmol Sharma]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>广播</category><category>Television Broadcasting</category><category>有线广播</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>技术</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Labor Disputes</category><category> Artificial Intelligence/Machine Learning</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Celebrities</category><category> Computer Science</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>Feature Films</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>电影</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>剧院</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Warner Bros. Discovery Inc. Series A</category><category> WBD</category><category> Paramount Global</category><category>帕拉</category><category>Warner Bros. Discovery</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>labor disputes</category><category> artificial intelligence</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>celebrities</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>feature films</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>movies</