          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826366?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Taiwan, home to TSMC, accounted for about 40% of the drop in China&#39;s chip imports during the first five months of the year.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Agence France-Presse/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097593"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dan-strumpf" itemprop="url" rel="author">Dan Strumpf</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/clarence-leong" itemprop="url" rel="author">Clarence Leong</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 31, 2023 5:39 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-tech-distress-grows-as-u-s-chip-sanctions-bite-3022475c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> HONG KONG—China&#39;s tech sector is showing the strain from last year&#39;s sweeping US export restrictions, which seek to stall Beijing&#39;s ambitions in cutting-edge industries such as artificial intelligence and supercomputing.</p><p> Semiconductor imports to China are falling. Chinese companies say they are struggling to get key components and machinery. And chipsets that have been remodeled to make them less powerful so they fall within US rules are now threatened by the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-considers-new-curbs-on-ai-chip-exports-to-china-56b17feb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">possibility of additional restrictions</a> .</p><p> The distress signals show Washington&#39;s nine-month-old policy of denying Beijing access to the most advanced semiconductors and the tools to make them is starting to bite, despite loopholes and workarounds keeping some key components flowing.</p><p> The restrictions also show the obstacles facing China in developing domestic alternatives for some of the most sought-after foreign semiconductor technologies. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="900" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824904?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “The controls appear to be making it harder and costlier for China to gain certain inputs,” said Emily Benson, a senior fellow specializing in trade and technology at the Center for Strategic and International Studies think tank.</p><p> Customs data released by Beijing this month highlighted the reality for Chinese buyers of high-end chips: Imports of semiconductors fell by 22% in value terms during the first six months of 2023 from a year earlier. Imports of chip-manufacturing equipment dropped by 23%, extending last year&#39;s decline.</p><p> Leading chip-manufacturing regions accounted for the lion&#39;s share of the decline in semiconductor imports. Taiwan, home to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSM" class="">Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing</a> <span class="company-name-type">Co.</span> , the world&#39;s largest chip maker, accounted for about 40% of the drop in China&#39;s chip imports during the first five months of the year. South Korea, home to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SSNHZ" class="">Samsung</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/KR/XKRX/000660" class="company-name">SK Hynix</a> and other chip giants, accounted for almost one-third.美国的限制影响了使用美国芯片制造工具的外国公司——几乎所有这些公司都这样做。</p><p> There are likely other factors at play behind drooping semiconductor imports.在全球需求疲软的情况下，中国经济正在放缓。北京还对国内科技行业进行了大量投资，以推动更大程度的自力更生，尽管这需要时间才能取得成果。 In the meantime, China lacks the ability to make the most advanced chips, with key elements in their supply chain controlled by the US and its allies. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826367?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Intel executives said the company was releasing a tweaked version of its Gaudi2 AI chip for the China market.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Mark Schiefelbein/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Japan on July 23 restricted the export of crucial semiconductor-manufacturing equipment, following curbs announced by the Netherlands.这两个国家和美国是制造最先进芯片所必需的一些机械的唯一制造商。</p><p> This month, the largest listed subsidiary of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/HK/XHKG/596" class="">Inspur</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> China&#39;s top maker of servers used to develop AI, issued a warning to investors: Citing tight supply, the company said it is struggling to get chips critical to powering its AI servers, the powerful machines used in laboratories and tech companies to develop advanced AI. The company said it could take a 30% hit to its revenue in the first half of the year as a result.</p><p> Unable to access the latest chips, China&#39;s AI contenders risk falling behind in a sector that Beijing has said it aims to lead the world in by 2030. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UBS" class="company-name">UBS</a> said it expects global demand for AI products to reach $300 billion by 2027, from $28 billion last year. Meanwhile, US <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-and-microsoft-paying-big-to-play-in-ai-48cae808?page=1&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">tech giants</a> including Microsoft, Google and Amazon are pumping billions into AI platforms unhindered.</p><p> Other Chinese companies are facing challenges getting parts. Late last month, China&#39;s leading maker of memory chips, Yangtze Memory Technologies, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-chip-industry-grim-but-defiant-as-new-u-s-sanctions-loom-73789348?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">urged suppliers to show “integrity”</a> and deliver machinery parts it had already purchased.</p><p> “We can&#39;t get the components, which we have bought legally,” said Nanxiang Chen, chairman and acting chief executive of YMTC, which is among the companies cited by the US that can&#39;t receive exports from America or its allies.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Do you think US tech restrictions will help America keep its lead in chips?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> A major Chinese tool maker at the same industry event in Shanghai said it must now apply for licenses through its US suppliers to obtain certain components. The license application procedure can take months, and there is no guarantee of receiving the components in the end, an employee at the Chinese tool maker said.</p><p> The US export rules announced Oct. 7 included caps on the power of certain processors used in AI applications and in supercomputers, as well as restrictions on the types of chip-making machinery, components and software China can import.</p><p> While selling top-end chips and tools to Chinese buyers may no longer be an option, some Western companies are benefiting from China&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-sanctions-drive-chinese-firms-to-advance-ai-without-latest-chips-f6aed67f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">accelerating buildup of domestic chip capacity</a> . ASML, the Dutch maker of lithography machines that are critical to chipmaking, posted a 27% rise in second-quarter revenue, driven in part by sales to China, its third-largest market during the period.</p><p> CEO Peter Wennink said China&#39;s demand for less-advanced machines that aren&#39;t affected by sanctions, is “very sustainable for the next couple of years,” because Chinese companies are investing in new factories to reduce reliance on imported chips.</p><p> At least two US chip giants have tweaked the specs on products to meet export-control thresholds. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVDA" class="company-name">Nvidia</a> last year released a chip for the China market <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nvidia-offers-alternative-chip-for-china-to-clear-u-s-export-hurdles-11667891718?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">called the A800</a> , a downgraded version of a high-end AI chip.随后又推出了另一款专注于中国的芯片，名为 H800。</p><p> Earlier this month, Intel executives said the company was releasing a tweaked version of its Gaudi2 AI chip for the China market.英特尔表示，它正在与浪潮合作提供该芯片。</p><p> Despite the new chips, Handel Jones, CEO of consulting firm International Business Strategies, said Inspur appears to be having “major problems” getting high-end processors from chip makers including Intel, AMD and Nvidia, and called Intel&#39;s new chip a “minor step” that could invite pressure from Washington. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=6F2E219F-28E7-43BF-88B8-CE785ACB359B&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchinas-tech-distress-grows-as-u-s-chip-sanctions-bite-3022475c&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> After working for years to catch up on US technology, China has developed a chip that can rival Nvidia&#39;s powerful A100.随着两个超级大国争夺人工智能的主导地位，《华尔街日报》对处理器的设计和功能进行了分析。 Illustration: Sharon Shi<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>The Biden administration is weighing further restrictions, including tighter exports to China of chips used in artificial intelligence, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-considers-new-curbs-on-ai-chip-exports-to-china-56b17feb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">The Wall Street Journal has reported</a> .</p><p> “Whether the controls remain successful or whether they inadvertently accelerate Chinese indigenization efforts” remains to be seen, said Benson from CSIS.</p><p> On July 3, China said it would <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-restricts-exports-of-two-metals-used-in-high-performance-chips-a649402b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">restrict exports of gallium</a> , used in some advanced semiconductors. More recently, China&#39;s ambassador to the US, Xie Feng, threatened further retaliatory action, saying that Beijing “won&#39;t flinch from any provocation.”</p><p> “It is like restricting the other side to wear outdated swimwear in a swimming contest, while you yourself are wearing a Speedo Fastskin,” Xie said, referring to what the iconic sportswear brand calls its most technologically advanced swimwear. “This isn&#39;t fair.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> — Yoko Kubota in Beijing contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Dan Strumpf at <a href="mailto:Dan.Strumpf@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Dan.Strumpf@wsj.com</a> and Clarence Leong at <a href="mailto:clarence.leong@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">clarence.leong@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 09:39:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-tech-distress-grows-as-us-chip-sanctions-bite-3022475c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-tech-distress-grows-as-us-chip-sanctions-bite-3022475c<author><![CDATA[Dan StrumpfClarence Leong]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>Semiconductors</category><category>工业电子</category><category>工业品</category><category>技术</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>semiconductors</category><category> industrial electronics</category><category>工业品</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Local Malls, Stuck in ‘Death Spiral,’ Plunge in Value]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>康涅狄格州水晶广场 (Crystal Mall) 2012 年价值 1.5 亿美元，最近以 950 万美元售出<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823519/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="康涅狄格州沃特福德市水晶购物中心的降价显示了近年来美国地区购物中心的命运下降的速度有多快。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>康涅狄格州沃特福德市水晶购物中心的降价显示了近年来美国地区购物中心的命运下降得有多快。约翰尼·米兰诺/彭博新闻<span>约翰尼·米兰诺/彭博新闻</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093483"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093483"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/kate-king" itemprop="url" rel="author">凯特·金</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 31 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/local-malls-stuck-in-death-spiral-plunge-in-value-a7998b7d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>康涅狄格州沃特福德——水晶购物中心的停车场过去非常拥挤，家长们会在其中一个入口附近排队送孩子下车，而不是寻找停车位。</p><p>现在，康涅狄格州海岸这座 20 世纪 80 年代的区域购物中心周围大片开裂的人行道上杂草比汽车还多。 2012 年，评估师对水晶广场的估价为 1.53 亿美元，6 月份的一次止赎拍卖中，水晶广场以略高于 950 万美元的价格售出。</p><p> “现在看来，这令人沮丧，”沃特福德的最高民选领导人、第一任议员罗布·布鲁尔(Rob Brule)说。他在这个工人阶级小镇长大，并将这座购物中心描述为他年轻时的社交中心。</p><p>水晶广场的降价显示，近年来，由于购物习惯的改变、来自其他零售业的竞争以及网上购物的兴起， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/shopping-mall-nostalgia-auction-420a44f9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国地区购物中心的价值</a>迅速恶化。</p><p>房地产研究公司 Green 的美国零售和工业研究主管文斯·蒂博恩 (Vince Tibone) 表示，较旧的低端购物中心的价值至少比 2016 年底购物中心估值达到顶峰时低 50%，在某些情况下还低 70% 以上。街道。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>据<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MCO" class="company-name">穆迪</a>分析公司称，现在，随着这些物业支持的超过 140 亿美元的贷款将在未来 12 个月内到期，陷入困境的购物中心正在拖欠债务。随着抵押贷款利率大幅上升，债务再融资将更具挑战性且成本更高。</p><p>穆迪商业房地产经济分析主管凯文·费根(Kevin Fagan)表示，通过商业抵押贷款支持证券融资的购物中心中，约有五分之一处于水下状态，这意味着这些房产的价值低于它们所支持的贷款。</p><p>在某些情况下，它们的价值要低得多。晶城广场的前所有者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SPG" class="">西蒙地产集团 (Simon Property Group)</a><span class="company-name-type">在</span>疫情期间停止支付 8100 万美元的未偿 CMBS 债务，并于去年归还了其自 1999 年以来拥有的房产的钥匙。</p><p>穆迪表示，这笔贷款被纳入由著名投资者卡尔·伊坎做空的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/carl-icahn-placing-a-big-bet-against-mall-owners-11574201244?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">CMBX 6 指数</a>中，预计清算时将损失 7000 万美元，约占未偿余额的 87%。</p><p>类似的故事正在全国各地上演。 Trepp 表示，在印第安纳州，Muncie Mall 提供了 3100 万美元的贷款，但经过 3 月份的评估后，其价值仅为 600 万美元。这家拥有 52 年历史的购物中心九年前估价为 7300 万美元，直到 2018 年才几乎客满。</p><p>特雷普表示，位于新泽西州中部的伍德布里奇中心 (Woodbridge Center) 是一家占地 110 万平方英尺的购物中心，今年早些时候的估值为 8600 万美元，比 2014 年疫情前的上次估值下降了 76%。该购物中心的两笔 CMBS 贷款被取消抵押品赎回权，未偿余额总计近 2.5 亿美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826219?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Trepp 高级董事总经理马努斯·克兰西 (Manus Clancy) 表示：“我们已经看到数十家购物中心因亏损而被清算或价值被削减。”</p><p>并非所有购物中心都处于灾难的边缘。较新、位置优越的房产和强大的租户名单正在为投资者带来健康的人流量和回报。但 Tibone 表示，自 2016 年以来，即使是这些高质量的购物中心，其价值也已下降了约 50%，使得购物中心成为同期表现最差的商业房地产行业之一。</p><p> 2018 年开始， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/retail-chains-shed-stores-but-it-isnt-good-for-business-11605436204?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">百货商店普遍关门，</a>加速了购物中心的衰落。大型商场主播喜欢</p>Green Street 的数据显示，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/M" class="">梅西百货</a><span class="company-name-type">、</span> Bon-Ton、JCPenney 和 Sears 在 2018 年至 2020 年底期间关闭了约 875 家百货商店，而 2016 年和 2017 年总共关闭了 175 家百货商店。<p></p><p> “这确实加速了该行业的死亡螺旋，”蒂博恩说。 “你开始失去百货商店，这导致中心的销售额和客流量下降。然后更多的租户离开。这就开始了这个可怕的循环。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=C72EA178-F0CA-46FE-B63D-3CE629CAF70C&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Flocal-malls-stuck-in-death-spiral-plunge-in-value-a7998b7d&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">大流行改变了我们的购物方式。更多的人在网上购物意味着更多的人退货。 《华尔街日报》的达尔文·布朗 (Dalvin Brown) 解释了一些公司如何利用零工为您带来这些回报。图片插图：方大卫<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>水晶广场的死亡螺旋始于 2018 年，当时主要租户<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sears-exit-would-leave-big-holes-in-malls-some-landlords-welcome-that-1539342000?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">西尔斯宣布破产</a>并宣布计划关闭。三年后，梅西百货关闭了门店。 Trepp 表示，2018 年至 2022 年间，水晶广场的总体收入下降了 39%，而支出仅下降了 10%。</p><p> “所有的商店都曾经营业过，一切都曾经美好而美丽，”最近的一个下午，40 岁的梅丽莎·罗德里格斯 (Melissa Rodriguez) 站在购物中心的美食广场外说道。</p><p>现在，很多商店都关门了。她最喜欢的商店之一<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BBBYQ" class="">Bed Bath &amp; Beyond</a><span class="company-name-type">在</span>今年早些时候<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/some-investors-arent-giving-up-on-bed-bath-beyond-7c1dcd37?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">宣布破产</a>后即将关闭。罗德里格斯说，在大流行之前，她经常每周去购物中心两次，但现在每月只来一次。</p><p> “这不像以前，”她说。</p><p>与 Bed Bath &amp; Beyond 共享主力空间的 Christmas Tree Shops <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/christmas-tree-shops-to-liquidate-all-stores-ea53da39?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">也在破产后关闭</a>。一旦这些零售商撤离，JCPenney 将成为晶苑广场唯一剩下的主力租户。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823825?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">近年来，随着西尔斯百货（Sears）和梅西百货（Macy&#39;s）这两家主力店的关闭，水晶广场陷入了衰落。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：约翰尼·米兰诺/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>沃特福德第一任议员布鲁尔表示，他希望看到该地产重新开发为综合用途场地。他设想为参观神秘岛附近的游客建造一座酒店，并为当地消防员、教师以及当地潜艇制造商通用动力电船公司的员工提供住房。也许是曲棍球场或保龄球馆，是镇上青少年聚集的地方。</p><p> “这就是这个财产可能的样子，”布鲁尔说。</p><p>水晶广场的这些梦想在其新东家、总部位于纽约的投资公司 Namdar Realty Group 的领导下不太可能实现。布鲁尔说，一位公司高管在一次介绍性电话会议上告诉布鲁尔，公司不会重新开发房产。</p><p> Namdar 首席执行官伊加尔·南达尔 (Igal Namdar) 表示，该公司计划实施“积极的租赁策略，以吸引全国和本地租户”到晶丽广场。</p><p>写信给凯特·金<a href="mailto:kate.king@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">kate.king@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/local-malls-stuck-in-death-spiral-plunge-in-value-a7998b7d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/local-malls-stuck-in-death-spiral-plunge-in-value-a7998b7d<author><![CDATA[Kate King]]></author><category>华尔街日报-美国新闻</category><category>商业地产</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>零售批发</category><category>混合零售</category><category>购物中心/超市</category><category>房地产服务/交易</category><category>零售房地产</category><category>商业/工业地产</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>房地产</category><category>零售</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>商业房地产</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>穆迪</category><category>MCO</category><category>床浴及其他</category><category>BBYQ</category><category>梅西百货</category><category>中号</category><category>西蒙地产集团</category><category>SPG</category><category>凯文·费根</category><category>罗布·布鲁尔</category><category>卡尔·伊坎</category><category>文斯·蒂伯恩</category><category>马努斯·克兰西</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>零售</category><category>批发的</category><category>混合零售</category><category>购物广场</category><category>超市</category><category>房地产服务</category><category>交易</category><category>零售房地产</category><category>商业的</category><category>工业地产</category><category>房地产</category><category>建造</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Benefit of Owning Stocks Over Bonds Keeps Shrinking]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>一些人担心，在股票相对价值指标跌至二十年来的低点后，涨势无法持续。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001094270"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826395?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">分析师表示，持有股票相对于债券的溢价不可能无限期地保持在这么低的水平。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：朱莉娅·尼欣森/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001094270"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sam-goldfarb" itemprop="url" rel="author">萨姆·戈德法布</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 31 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-benefit-of-owning-stocks-over-bonds-keeps-shrinking-20528203"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>持有股票而非债券的额外回报已降至20年来的最低水平，威胁到主要股指近期的连涨。</p><p>衡量股票价值的一种方法是将其收益率（通过将公司明年的预期收益除以其股价计算得出）与政府债券的收益率进行比较，政府债券被认为是最接近无风险回报的收益率。这种差异有时被称为股权风险溢价，表明投资者因持有股票的额外风险而获得了多少补偿。</p><p>而现在，这还不算多。</p><p>上周，标准普尔 500 指数的盈利收益率与美国 10 年期国债收益率之间的差距降至 1.1 个百分点左右，为 2002 年以来的最低水平。 10 年期美国国债通胀保值证券收益率的利差一些分析师认为这是更好的基准，因为企业盈利<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-is-inflation-so-sticky-it-could-be-corporate-profits-b78d90b7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">往往会随着通货膨胀而调整</a>，但同样也跌至 2003 年以来的最低水平，约为 3.5 个百分点。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您对股票和债券的态度是什么？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>风险溢价从去年下半年开始开始下降。在此期间，股市从年初的抛售中企稳，尽管债券收益率因美联储加息以应对通胀而持续攀升。今年，溢价<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/stocks-havent-looked-this-unattractive-since-2007-78fc374c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">继续下降，</a>原因略有不同：债券收益率没有上升那么多，但股票却在投资者对经济日益乐观的推动下飞涨。</p><p>无论发生什么变化，华尔街都有一个共识，即股票风险溢价不可能永远保持在这么低的水平。</p><p>研究和投资策略主管 Tim Urbanowicz 表示，如果股价相对于收益的比率回到 2022 年抛售开始时的水平，“当利率比原来高出 2 倍、3 倍时，这确实不合理”。创新者 ETF。</p><p>投资者和分析师也倾向于认为，超低的风险溢价并不意味着今年的股市上涨已经结束。</p><p>他们指出，一方面，在 20 世纪 90 年代末的互联网泡沫时期，风险溢价已经低得多。根据一些衡量标准，当时标准普尔 500 指数的盈利收益率与通胀调整后的或“实际”国债收益率之间的差距一度完全缩小。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826036?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">美联储主席杰罗姆·鲍威尔上周表示，可能会再次加息，但也暗示利率可能保持稳定。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Al Drago/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>回顾历史，分析师表示，随着时间的推移，风险溢价会恢复到平均水平，这通常是因为企业盈利前景黯淡，而不是因为投资者本身被估值吓坏了。</p><p>布莱恩·雅各布森 (Brian Jacobsen) 表示：“我还没有发现相对于 10 年期国债的收益率（无论是实际收益还是名义收益）与一年期或三年期的未来收益之间存在很强的统计关系。”附属财富管理公司首席经济学家。</p><p>投资者还有另一个希望来源：风险溢价可能会正常化，因为债券收益率下降，而不是股票价格下降。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-07-25-2023/card/is-the-fed-prepping-its-final-interest-rate-hike--9HVDuRwso3GtKrz2IhkL?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">许多人相信美联储终于不再加</a>息，这加剧了这种乐观情绪。</p><p>根据芝商所数据，随着通胀显示出降温迹象，利率期货表明投资者认为美联储今年再次加息的可能性仅略高于 30%。在周三的新闻发布会上，美联储主席杰罗姆·鲍威尔<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">为再次加息敞开了大门</a>，但也表示，如果经济数据配合，央行可能会选择在一段时间内保持利率稳定。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>美国国债收益率在很大程度上反映了投资者对债券期限内短期利率的预期。即使美联储的紧缩行动已经结束，如果央行将利率维持在当前水平的时间比投资者预期的时间长，债券收益率也可能进一步上升。</p><p>尽管如此，人们的共识是利率和债券收益率最终都会下降。</p><p>这一观点已经体现在当前的债券收益率中。根据 Tradeweb 的数据，截至周五，基准 10 年期国债通胀保值债券的收益率约为 1.6%。然而，五年期TIPS收益率为1.9%，这意味着投资者预计未来10年下半年实际短期利率将低于上半年。</p><p>与此同时，大多数美联储官员在 6 月份预计实际利率最终将稳定在不高于 0.5% 的水平。</p><p> Annex Wealth Management 的 Jacobsen 表示，他认为未来 12 至 18 个月内 10 年期 TIPS 收益率可能会降至 0.75% 或 1%。</p><p>这意味着，假设指数不会进一步大幅上涨，投资者就会因持有股票而获得更多回报。但这也意味着债券价格已经上涨。雅各布森表示，他的团队最近建议客户在此前更倾向于股票之后，将更多资金转向债券。</p><p>他表示：“如果你看看从 1989 年至今的加息周期，每次利率达到平台期时，这对债券来说都是相当利多的，我们认为我们至少已经接近那个点了。”</p><p>写信给 Sam Goldfarb： <a href="mailto:sam.goldfarb@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sam.goldfarb@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/e0815ea6-ecc0-4136-bdae-5d2167589c29.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-benefit-of-owning-stocks-over-bonds-keeps-shrinking-20528203</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-benefit-of-owning-stocks-over-bonds-keeps-shrinking-20528203<author><![CDATA[Sam Goldfarb]]></author><category>华尔街日报财经</category><category>华尔街日报金融市场</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>股票市场</category><category>债务/债券市场</category><category>商品/金融市场新闻</category><category>政府债务/债券市场</category><category>国家政府债务/债券市场</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>股票市场</category><category>债务</category><category>债券市场</category><category>商品</category><category>金融市场新闻</category><category>政府债务</category><category>国家政府债务</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Don’t Be a Jerk at Work. (But Don’t Be Too Nice, Either.)]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>讨好别人会如何阻碍你的职业生涯<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825131/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption><span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001091056"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001091056"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rachel-feintzeig"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-736144/AM" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rachel-feintzeig" itemprop="url" rel="author">Rachel Feintzeig</a></span>照片插图和<span class="author" itemprop="name">视频由 Aaron DuRall 为《华尔街日报》拍摄</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 30 日晚上 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dont-be-a-jerk-at-work-but-dont-be-too-nice-either-cf5d61e8"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>工作时你应该表现得有多好？</p><p>据说我们已经摆脱了军国主义首席执行官发出命令和威胁的时代。我们大多数人都同意：我们<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/office-jerk-how-to-tell-9f69a49f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">不喜欢混蛋</a>。善待我们​​，我们恳求我们的孩子。</p><p>然后我们到办公室。我们有需要召集的直接下属、需要说服<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/voluntold-voluntelling-work-tips-1aadced1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的其他部门的同事</a>以及声称需要诚实反馈的老板。说话时犹豫不决，就会被忽视。小心翼翼地对待你的团队，你就是一个容易被打败的人，而不是一支不可忽视的力量。</p><p> “就我个人而言，我认为你是一个太好的人，不适合从事现在的工作。”这是北卡罗来纳州共和党众议员格雷格·墨菲 (Greg Murphy) 在今年春天的一次听证会上对美国首席贸易谈判代表凯瑟琳·戴 (Katherine Tai) 所说的话。他的评论总结了我们很多人，尤其是女性，所听到的反馈。我们太活泼或太善良。我们使用了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/want-power-stop-saying-sorry-so-much-11666479801?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">太多的道歉</a>或<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/shes-not-mad-shes-just-not-using-exclamation-points-1540267501?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">感叹号</a>。然而，当我们在这方面做得太少时，我们就会过于激进。</p><p> “我想成为一个好人，”一家医疗咨询公司的运营总监莎拉·克莱因伯格（Sarah Kleinberg）告诉我。但她意识到，友善往往会让别人感觉良好，但实际上并没有推动项目前进或促使团队成员改进。</p><p> “你必须有<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brag-at-work-without-sounding-like-a-jerk-11675008352?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">足够的自信</a>才能取悦别人，”她说。</p><h3> “客户服务声音”</h3><p>许多人不顾一切地不想冒犯他人，于是求助于口语教练萨马拉·贝所说的“客户服务之声”。这是一种高调、高调的语气，旨在告诉咖啡师，<em>我想你可能没有燕麦奶了？</em></p><p>当我们使用这种语气时我们在说什么？ “我并不强大，别担心，”贝说。</p><p>她补充道，让自己变得不那么令人生畏、尽可能地小可能会在职业生涯的早期发挥作用，让负责人感到安全。但当我们上升或尝试上升时，摇摆不定的声音可能会让其他人感到困惑。贝说，如果做得足够多，人们可能会质疑你是否适合领导。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="482" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825189?width=700&amp;height=482" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div><p>她建议进行发声练习，以便<a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/CvILkq-plHW/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">更自信地说话</a>。假装你正在自我介绍——“嗨，我叫雷切尔”——同时向墙上扔一个假装的球。让你的音调与球的轨迹相匹配。当您将球扔到地上时，您会听到您的声音随着球一起减弱。然后把球抛起来，注意你说话的方式，听起来好像你正在收回它们。最后，把球直接扔出去，让你的话也能贯穿始终。</p><p> “从头到尾说出某件事并始终坚持下去是一种最奇怪的感觉，”贝说。 “感觉很勇敢。”</p><h3>不允许对冲</h3><p>谈判教练鲍勃·博尔多内 (Bob Bordone) 表示，在提出想法时，不要用对冲语言来削弱自己的地位。他对这样的问题感到畏缩：“你愿意考虑让我<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hack-your-workweek-to-leave-early-on-summer-fridays-9752ee8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在周五远程工作</a>吗？”</p><p> “这让我只想说不，因为这是一件很脆弱的事情，”他说。</p><p>相反，他说，从一个声明开始：“我想和你谈谈制定一个新的时间表。”确保您达成的任何协议都对您的经理和公司有利。</p><p>当有人告诉你“不”时，博尔多内建议尝试：“即使我们有不同的看法，我们该如何解决这个问题？”他说，你听起来坚强、自信，但并不令人讨厌。</p><p>对于我们这些好人来说，好消息是：你不必放弃自己的个性才能得到认真对待。</p><p> “99.9% 的时间里，我都是一个快乐、无忧无虑的人，”华盛顿州温哥华市的用户体验设计师兼教育家 Colton Schweitzer 说道。当他不喜欢项目的发展方向时，他通过提出问题并偶尔插入笑话来反驳。</p><p> “我在微笑，”他说，“即使我说，‘你确定吗？’”</p><p>因为他非常令人愉快，所以他的严肃时刻很有分量。在一份工作中，当同事要求时，他很乐意承担更多的工作，直到他的经理要求他填补一名表现不佳的员工的空缺。他坚决地拒绝了。他说，他的经理放弃了这个问题，并对他的回应感到惊讶和印象深刻。</p><p> “这就像一种货币，”他谈到更严厉的风格时说道。 “当我使用它时，它真的很有价值。”</p><h3>少一点叫喊，多一点强度</h3><p>西北大学凯洛格管理学院领导力教授哈里·克雷默表示，要强硬但不生涩，就要设定明确的期望。</p><p>在任教之前，Kraemer 升任<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BAX" class="">Baxter International</a>的首席执行官<span class="company-name-type">，</span>他在这家医疗保健公司工作了 25 年。作为一名新经理，他会努力成为每个人的轻松朋友，当他的团队在截止日期后几小时提交项目时，他会不屑一顾。第二次发生时，他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/boss-management-yelling-workplace-cf32b09a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">开始大喊大叫</a>，却发现自己从一开始就没有讲清楚其中的利害关系。</p><p> “如果我专注于被人喜欢，那么受到尊重的机会就非常低，”他说。</p><p>他采用了一种新的领导风格：“我不会让你感到惊讶。”他说，大喊大叫让他看起来失去了控制，但采取行动的结果奏效了。当他的团队未能完成销售目标时，他会召集他们进行两个小时的汇报——没有微笑，他的声音很紧张。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/atmospheric/amp.html?guid=8580B420-EE92-4C60-AB07-B0296746C53B" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"><span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“我不需要抱歉，”他会告诉他们。 “按号码。做你告诉我你要做的事。”</p><p>黛娜·戴维斯 (Dinah Davis) 是北卡罗来纳州高地市的一名房地产经纪人，她仍然记得多年前一位老朋友在高尔夫球场上给她的建议。这位朋友是一位技术精湛的神经外科医生，以直率、不敏感而闻名。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>你认为你在工作中可能太好了吗？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> “我对待病人的态度很好，”她告诉戴维斯。 “我只是没有时间。”</p><p>这个建议让戴维斯松了一口气，他曾是一名律师，更喜欢坚定的谈判，而不是欢快的闲聊。</p><p> “你希望你的飞行员表现得友善吗？”戴维斯问道。 “或者你想让你的飞行员让飞机降落在地面上？”</p><p>写信给 Rachel Feintzeig，邮箱为<a href="mailto:Rachel.Feintzeig@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Rachel.Feintzeig@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/abc0d988-98a3-49dd-87e2-f6d4256e8c3e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/dont-be-a-jerk-at-work-but-dont-be-too-nice-either-cf5d61e8</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/dont-be-a-jerk-at-work-but-dont-be-too-nice-either-cf5d61e8<author><![CDATA[Rachel Feintzeig]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>百特国际</category><category>巴克斯</category></item></channel></rss>